review.reviewBody:
Not quite as big as we hoped BUT big enough and a good size to still carry easily. The squared off size makes it very easy to pack.
The straps are a little cumbersome to get on and off no quick clips which for such an expensive bag is a feature I was just expecting to be there. Overall it is a good bag but I would wait until it was on sale to buy. . . .
review.name: We really love our Allpa Duffel

review.reviewBody: Roller derby gal here! The Allpa 70L Duffel is exactly what the roller derby gods ordered!! Perfectly sized with more than enough room to fit a pair of quad skates, two helmets, protective gear, and at least three to five changes of clothes including multiple shoes. Best part, I can still get it on the plane as a personal item because it compacts well enough. Have skates, have duffel, will travel!
review.name: Winner! Winner! Vegan Chick’n Dinner!

review.reviewBody: Was looking for a bag with a separate compartment to store snowboard boots, and a main compartment large enough to store outerwear, helmet, base layers, gloves, etc. etc. This bag checks all of those things, plus the durable materials!
review.name: Snowboard Bag!

review.reviewBody: Bought this to travel via plane for a month long sailing trip and had more than enough room. Weighs a lot less than a hard shell suitcase and easy to wear using the backpack straps.
review.name: Love this

review.reviewBody: My son is going on a school trip to Scotland & England, next summer. I wanted to get him something easy to pack and carry. The fact that it could be worn as a backpack was a huge plus. My son loved that it came in his favorite color (orange).
review.name: Great bag! Seems to be great quality.

review.reviewBody: The quality of this item exceeded my expectations. It is light weight and well made. Love the color combinations.
review.name: First time buyer won’t be the last!

review.reviewBody: so happy to travel with my cotopaxi bag i love the colors
review.name: awesome!

review.reviewBody: I purchased this bag for a 1 year solo travel. I needed something big enough to carry everything I may or may not need for a year, a duffel style open for convenience, back pack straps for carrying long distance and with room for a few souvenirs along the way. After looking into a billion bags, this was the only one that fit my needs and it's quality has exceeded my expectations.
review.name: Ready for the world

review.reviewBody: Love the color scheme, love that it comes in a mesh case. I bought it for a 2 week trip happening in a few weeks!
review.name: Love the color scheme, love

review.reviewBody: We are going on a Safari in Kenya and we can only take a soft sided bag with weight restrictions on the small plane to get us into the Masai Mara. We will be leaving our main luggage in Nairobi. This is the perfect backpack/duffle to use. We looked at many others just like it but found we really wanted the separate bottom compartment for shoes or dirty clothes. So excited for our trip.
review.name: Exactly what I needed for Africa

review.reviewBody: I have worn C3 bibs before and these are similar but not exactly the same.  Overall they are comfortable and I expect them to wear for a long time as my other three pairs of Gore bibs have. review.itemreviewed: Madson II Chore WP Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: Bought these for my husband and he love them.  We had to size up a half size since they run a little small.   You can dress them up or down and will be a perfect item for take on our travels!

review.itemreviewed: Madson II Chore WP Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: Fantastic boot, super comfortable right out of the box. Sufficiently wide in the toe box (I usually wear a EE boot).
review.name: Great boot made even better with a great price.

review.itemreviewed: Madson II Chore WP Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: These boots look and feel great to wear. Casual and still a bit dressy at the same time…They are great to wear out to dinner and also out in the rain and snow. The only fault is on the sole of the boot where the SOREL logo is in a dipped white rubber over the other part of the sole. I’ve only had the boots a few months with very little wear and the white rubber of the logo is peeling off of one of the soles. I know it’s a small thing but it really diminishes the overall look and feel of these nice boots. Especially when out and you happen to cross your legs or have your feet up on an ottoman. Picky… sure. But it just is a bummer that it’s that way. Otherwise a really nice boot.
review.name: Great boot with one unfortunate issue

review.itemreviewed: Madson II Chore WP Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: It is a nice boot for foul city weather and comfortable underfoot.  Unfortunately, they fail to cover the top of the heel cup leaving a thin, hard plastic ridge that on a long walk scrapes through your sock and removes the skin from your heel leaving a nasty and painful wound.  I hope a trip to the cobbler who can add a leather membrane will fix it.  But you are left to wonder who and anyone would make a boot that has a jagged ridge on the heel.
review.name: Design Flaw
comment: Hello Kyle, we appreciate you sharing your feedback and we're sorry Men's Madson™ II Chore Boot didn't meet your standards. We will inform our product team of your concerns and ensure this is fixed for the future.

The dark brown, suede-like material, cap toe appearance makes the boot look professional that you can dress up or down.  The boots are very comfortable.  Also, I’ve worn these through puddles and rain and the waterproofing is superb.

review.reviewBody: Recently purchased this shirt at a local outdoor shop. Probably the best fitting shirt I own. At 5'11, 180lbs, I typically fall right in between medium and large for most brands. Medium tends to be on the verge of too tight and large tends to be baggy. The Ovik twill in medium is a perfect fit. Exactly right across the shoulders, perfect length, and doesn't billow around the waist. Quality is top notch.
review.name: Finally a true Medium.

review.reviewBody: Bought as gift for husband. The deep forest/green looks great. Definitely a high quality shirt.
review.name: Looks and fits great

review.reviewBody: I'd guess the Ovik Twill is made from close to a 6 oz per yard cotton twill, making it a midweight flannel. It has a nice heft to it. My XL shirt has a 52" chest, meaning Fjallraven designs their "relaxed fit" Ovik Twill shirt with a ~7" clearance (see Fjallraven's Size Guide, Backcountry's Size Chart is - frustratingly - different). I have a 46" chest (so I should have gotten an XXL), but my XL is still a bit loose. One could probably size down one (or two) sizes and have a shirt with a slimmer fit. The box pleat in the back will help with shoulder and arm mobility. The biggest complaint regarding size is that the sleeves run long (mine is over 36" long). As with most Fjallraven shirts, the length is also long, but this is useful for cold weather. Unfortunately, the Autumn Leaf/Dark Navy colorway is more orange and black (not navy) and the shirt has an overall dark/black coloring to it that is not represented well in the stock image. If you are familiar with Fjallraven's unique fit then there is nothing too new in my review regarding sizing, but the color inaccuracy is most unfortunate. It's still a nice, warm midweight flannel, however, and maybe the color will fade to what is advertised after a few washes.
review.name: Ovik Twill is Nice Midweight Shirt, Big!

review.reviewBody: Jacket fits true to size and I love the green color. Can’t wait to try it out on the slopes!

review.itemreviewed: Recon Stretch Ski Shell Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: I knocked a star because I wish there were two front chest pockets. I’ve learned in snow activities I utilize the chest pockets more than the lower jacket pockets (mainly because things slide out of my lower pockets all the time). Otherwise, this is a great shell and so far has been very waterproof!

review.itemreviewed: Recon Stretch Ski Shell Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: Bought this for a big trip to Japan last month and by the time it arrived I didn’t have time to return it or find something else. It’s a very strange fit. I’m short - 5’0 120# with a typical women’s body, meaning I have hips. It barely zips over my them, very tight and then rides up around my chest with all kinds of extra fabric bunched around my face. I have to snap the powder skirt first to be able to zip it up. It works great for what it’s designed for and the pockets are good, but it sure doesn’t fit me well. The hood is so massive you can’t wear it without a helmet (i.e. uphill on the skin track) because it falls down to my nose. I wish I could attach a photo - I don’t seem to have that option? It seems to be designed for men or women 5’6 and up with no hips.
review.name: Very strange fit

review.itemreviewed: Recon Stretch Ski Shell Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I'm loving my shell so far. The waterproofing beads everywhere, the length is great and it is comfortable. I've gotten lots of compliments on the look and colour. I had been nervous that it wouldn't be warm enough for cooler days on the chairlift but I've been happy with just a fleece or mid weight puffy underneath. 
My only notes are really specific, the arms are a bit baggy and the extra fold of material at the pockets lays in a weird way affecting the 'sleekness' of the fit .
review.name: Great jacket

review.itemreviewed: Recon Stretch Ski Shell Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: So glad I bought this jacket to replace my previous hard shell. It packs down smaller in my touring pack and it’s more flexible with greater coverage than the jacket I had before. And it’s easy to fit over my helmet for the blustery transitions or descents when I need a little more warmth.
review.name: Best shell for ski touring

review.itemreviewed: Recon Stretch Ski Shell Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody:
Bought this for my wife, 5’ 6”160 lbs and a large was perfect. First time out was a rainy PNW day and she stayed perfectly
dry and warm the whole time. Water was beading off right out of the package with no waterproofing done. Loved it so much i bought one for myself.
review.name: Amazing purchase

review.reviewBody: I've been riding TIME mtb pedals for 20 years, since the first time I got frustrated with mud-packing on other brands.  I've never had an issue with TIME (except when I've bashed into a log or root, and gotten wood stuck in the spring). I have never used the platform design for riding unclipped downhill which is (i think) one of the intended purposes, but the 2 reasons I continue to get the platform are 1) it works great for getting started on an uphill so you can get some momentum while trying to get the cleat inserted, & 2) I can use these with regular shoes while riding around the neighborhood with my kids. review.reviewBody: The rocket plus might not be for everyone, but I’m happy with 13cm & 16cm screws I’ve purchased. Using them feels a bit like “sport climbing” on ice, they bite instantly and drive fast; clip and go. They do have some design “hiccups” imo, sometimes the free-spinning quick-draw hanger will catch and have to be corrected while turning the knob. Also, I do wish Camp would have integrated the “fold-up” turn knob (like the normal Rocket screw). I suppose it is a minor thing, but the turn knob can end up in bad positions after full placement, requiring a slight “back-out” of the screw. Also, I’ve not fallen on them. The entire screw/draw setup w/Nano 22 carabiner weighs less than my old BD express screw of the same size. Although, I would use a larger carabiner (Camp Photon) because the Nano 22 is a bit small while wearing gloves to clip efficiently each time. Overall, I’m happy with the purchase and will hopefully use them for many seasons.

I have sensitive skin and the fabric feels silky and not at all itchy, icebreaker is my favorite brand for wool clothes bc they have the softest, silkiest knits. review.reviewBody: I live in wool tank tops year-round. It is extremely rare that I am not wearing one, even if it is as a first layer during colder months. In this style (no matter what brand), you almost always need to SIZE DOWN one size; and some people may even go down two sizes. Ordinarily, I do not even like the "muscle" tee/tank style, but this one has a perfect feminine cut, while still embodying the strong, confident vibe many of us appreciate. For reference, I wear a medium in the Siren tank, and a small in the 125 Cool-Lite Sphere III tank. In most Icebreaker pieces, whether top or bottom, I generally prefer size medium, but every now and then I like a large (for instance, in some full-length leggings). I already have stacks of the Siren tanks, and now I have a growing stack of these as well; both are year-round daily staples I will not live without. While it is true that not every one of these tanks is consistently assembled and/or symmetrically proportioned, for most brands, I am long accustomed to ordering multiple units and returning those that do not fit perfectly. Yes, it is a hassle, but I am used to it, and this tank is SO worth it. Icebreaker, if you are reading this, please do NOT change a thing about the size small in this style (except for general quality control and manufacturing consistency). I have a long torso, long arms, and the dimensions are absolutely perfect for me. This tank is SO soft, tremendously comfortable, and incomparably feather-light. It feels like wearing nothing. As with many Icebreaker pieces, this garment dramatically decreases stress on a daily basis, and instantly became an indispensable element of my minimalist wardrobe. Thank you!
review.name: Outstanding Do It All Tank Top (Size Down)

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Fabric was nice, but armholes were gigantic on the size L. Going down a size would have made the tank too tight in midsection and still gaping at armholes. The overall cut was just too long in the torso for my 5' 3" frame.

review.reviewBody: I purchased the Smith Mission MIPS Helmet in White as a gift. The recipient is an avid skier and is absolutely delighted with the helmet. She tried it on right away and said the fit is perfect. A quality helmet is essential and Smith makes a great one! Also, Backcountry is a fantastic company and I purchased a number of items this year and last. Communication is great, as are the prices. I will not be returning anything but they do offer a liberal return policy if needed. Backcountry makes shopping a pleasure!
review.name: Excellent purchase

review.reviewBody: This helmet is so comfortable it feels like an extension of my body. The fit is customizable to your preferences, it has the prefect amount of ventilation when you need to cool down but also keeps your head warm and snuggled. I have worn it with a balaclava and had no issues with the fit. It's like a dream! Perfectly integrates with the aleck speakers and smith 4d mag goggles which are a must have as well!
review.name: Buy it now!

review.reviewBody: I bought a month ago and have skied with it once. Fit great right out of the box with a little fine tuning by turning the knob. Kept my noggin warm and like being to open and close the vents depending on conditions. Only knock is its a little harder to hear with this helmet than my old one.
review.name: Fits great

review.reviewBody: Took a pretty hard fall right onto my forehead. I think this helmet saved me from a concussion.

review.reviewBody: The colors are really nice and my boyfriend love them. It was exactly what he needed. The perfect gift if the person runs on different landscapes.

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Very comfortable. My feet feel solid and supported on my longer runs. I have run on a mixture of surfaces and grip has been consistently good, although I have not yet tested them in deep mud. I will certainly keep using them for my longer sorties and races.
BTW I took a size bigger to allow for foot expansion, which was needed.
review.name: Very pleased!

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: Great fit, snug through arch but with enough room in toe box to accommodate a slightly wider fore foot.

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I have the Aero Glide road shoes which are super comfortable! So I thought I’d give the Ultra Glides a try and they haven’t disappointed, very comfortable and excellent grip. Brilliant!!
review.name: Grip and comfort!

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: What I was looking for…support, cushioned, comfort. Turning this shoe into every day active wear. Just recently purchased and will test thru trails in upcoming trip to Thailand.
review.name: Shock absorbers

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody:
This is my third or fourth pair of the Ultra Glides. They are close fitting without feeling snug. well cushioned without feeling heavy and last for miles and miles (I get about 400 miles before I start to feel like they are starting to go).

I'll keep buying these as long as they keep making them.
review.name: Comfort and Control Mile After Mile

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: These shoes have become my favorite trail shoes. I’m about to purchase my 5th pair. I get 350+ miles out of each pair. I run on pretty rugged, rocky Arizona trails and these shoes handle it all really well. They feel comfortable in every aspect - good volume and perfect amount of cushion. They protect your feet from rocks while still giving you great ground feel. They even feel great on the road. I definitely recommend this shoe.
review.name: My Go-To Trail Shoe

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: Wonderful shoes and love the colors. Extremely comfortable and easy to get in and out of on the go.
review.name: Ultra Glide 2

review.itemreviewed: Ultra Glide Trail Running Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Although supports you well while running, the tightness is a serious issue.
After wearing it daily for about 5 months, corns have appeared on both my feet. And it is not only about uncomfortableness, the upper layer squeaks as I walk and doesn't fix.
review.name: Tight, Squeaking, but Soft at Bottom

review.reviewBody: I love the blue color and the look of the bag, however due to the design of the zipper, everything falls out when you open it. I also would love if it had a buckle on the strap for easy on/off and versatility of wear.
review.name: Almost great

review.reviewBody:
I really wanted to like this. It looked really cute online. But in real life, it is a weird shape. The back panel is extremely stiff like a backpack and so the bag sticks out rather than sitting against the body. The placement of the zipper is really awkward -- I can't put too much in the bag because I am afraid it will all fall out when I try to open it. It is also very clearly not for use in an urban area because any of the pockets could be easily accessed by pickpockets. I suppose if you are far from any potential thieves and can angle it so you are wearing it flat across your back and don't plan to open it for a very long time after packing it, this bag could be great! But that isn't what I need a bag for. Oh well! At least the color is accurate.

Update: May 2024: I've been revisiting this bag these past few months, and, while it still has the drawbacks described above, I'm updating my rating from 2 stars/5 out of 10 to 3 stars/7 out of 10. It will never be my primary bag, but I'm finding use for it as a backup bag I can leave at work to have on hand for occasional on-the-job errands. For that I'll give credit where credit is due.
review.name: Weird shape

review.reviewBody: I give 4 Stars because I like to look, the style and the material.  Outside of that the fit is much too tight and it doesn't have a 2 way zipper so it would have been nice to have one small back pocket for easier access gel packs or energy bars. I am 5'9", 164 lbs, 41" chest, 32" waist and I normally wear a medium and sometimes a large.  I have an older Castelli Wind Vest in a large and it is a relaxed fit. I have an older Castelli jersey in a large and it fits very nice, not tight, not loose, just right. I ordered the Squadra Vest in a large and the fit is more of a Race Fit, very tight. review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I was really hoping to like this Coleman Onesource Cordless Vacuum a lot more. I'll start off with some of the pros that I liked. One, it's cordless and the battery life is really good. It's USB Rechargeable and comes with the cord. You will need a power source to plug the cord in to. But, it stays up for weeks, fully charged with occasional use. Two, this is the perfect size for a handheld vacuum. The handle makes it easy to use, and hold. Plus it's not very heavy at all, roughly 5 pounds if that. Three, the push power button option is easy to use. Four, it's not very loud which I really liked.
Now onto the one con I had, which is the most important one when getting a vacuum. The suction power, this one just doesn't have any suction power at all. It will pick up some dust and dirt but that's about it. If you're wanting to use it to clean out the car for example, it's not going to do it. I also want to add I let this fully charge before using. I tried to vacuum my car out and it just wasn't picking anything up besides dust and dirt. It would occasionally pick up grass, but it's very time consuming as I had to keep going over and over the area. It would literally take hours to try and vacuum out the car with this, and it still wouldn't get it all the way clean. Overall, I wouldn't recommend this one until the suction power was made way stronger. If that was redone, this would honestly be perfect.

review.reviewBody:
After taking a good hit, my old helmet had a crack in the foam (not the exterior shell, check inside!) and upgraded to the Sweet Protection Bushwhacker II MIPS after the recommendation from my gearhead Mike. MIPS/protection and comfort were my primary concerns with finding a new helmet, and the Bushwhacker fits that bill! I have ~30hrs of mountain biking and 15hrs of gravel biking in this helmet.

Construction of the helmet appears to be solid. The dial adjustment at the rear is easy to manipulate. The visor is adequate, without getting in the way. The MIPS systems appears to be a little more free to move in this helmet vs. my old one (Bontrager). I've stashed sunglasses on the back of the helmet securely through some rowdy descents at sunset without worry. The ventilation is significantly better in the Bushwhacker, noticeable on the first ride. It's humid here in the summer (western NC mountains) and this helmet stays comfortable, while feeling like enough protection for the steep/technical/rocky trails around here.

Excellent helmet.
review.name: well ventilated, comfortable, & safe

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Hours spent in the rain wind and cold at a Morgan State Football Game the jacket kept my t shirt dry throughout confirmed in the bathroom at halftime and when I got home. Definitely windproof cause it was windy and chilly. The shell absorbs water doesn't repel. The inner shell keeps you dry. The inner pockets were damp I suppose from my body heat. My cellphone was damp as well. The hood will keep your head dry. Inclement weather wear something warm beneath the jacket. I suffered entire game with just a t shirt. I'd recommend further research on rain jackets to a friend before buying this one

review.reviewBody: This was purchased for a trip to the UK and IR where the weather can switch rapidly and I wanted a lightweight outer layer to go over my sweater or nano puff when the rains came and which I could tuck into a pack or shoulder bag if not needed. Went for my first walk in a Calgary drizzle, not heavy rain. Perhaps my expectations were too high but the outside didn't shed well at all and I started to feel damp about an hour into the walk. Got back home and the outside was soaked and the inside was a bit damp - a bit hard to tell when the jacket came off, it could have been a combo of seep through and breathability. However I hung the jacket up and 2 hours later the outside it is still soaking wet outside. For short showers it may work well but for heavy or extended rains it won't keep you dry. It did seem wind proof and the underarm vents are nice. I suspect that with rain jackets as with many other type of gear you have three variables - cost/weight & durability or a similar characteristic ie water resistance. You can only have two out of three. In the case cost and weight/pack ability is good but don't expect waterproof. So you really have to know what you want this for as this isn't waterproof over extended time or really heavy weather.
review.name: Probably not

review.reviewBody:
I am super glad to finally have the Adrenaline GTS 24’s!  I am not a runner, but I walk a ton. These shoes have all the right support and cushion for me to wear them all day long teaching PE and being an athletic trainer. Sometimes 15-16 hour days on Fridays. 
I have owned the Adrenaline 22’s, 23’s, & now the 24’s. They are  welcome addition to my daily workouts, teaching, & athletic training.
review.name: Good for Training, Teaching, & Workouts.

review.reviewBody: Although I'm not a runner, just a fast and sometimes casual walker, I have to say these are still a very comfortable and easy to wear shoe, no hot spots, at least for me, as I've got the adrenalines from way back to the 11's when I first discovered them (and still have them all to this day, [I'm not hard on shoes, and basically collect them] . I'll keep buying them as long as they still feel and look good.
review.name: Love all my Brooks!

review.reviewBody:
I’m all for innovation, but really? This latest release has been a huge letdown for me…

As a loyal fan of the Adrenaline GTS for over five years, I’ve always looked forward to the usual seamless transition from one model to the next. However, this year’s Adrenaline GTS 24 has been a completely different story.

From the very first run, I developed a blister on the inside of my left foot. Upon closer inspection, I noticed a hard seam where the upper material joins—something new to this model. This design change has turned out to be a major issue.

After contacting Brooks, I followed their advice and visited a local distributor to have my sizing reassessed. I ended up going half a size up and switching to a regular width instead of my usual wide. While this adjustment made the shoes feel closer to my GTS 23s, I hoped (desperately!) that it would solve the problem.

Sadly, it didn’t. While the GTS 24s are okay for my short morning runs, any longer distances bring back the blisters—this time on both feet. I can’t believe Brooks released a shoe with such a significant flaw. For me, it’s just completely broken.

When I run, the last thing I want to think about is my footwear. Unfortunately, with the GTS 24s, after about 3k every stride is a reminder of what’s wrong with them. Even the supposedly new and improved foam cushioning feels fairly flat and isn’t a noticeable improvement. I’m not interested in being a test subject for live product innovation. I want the reliable, no-nonsense, unfashionable shoes I’ve come to count on over the years. This shoe really is innovation for innovation’s sake at the cost of discernible progress and, in my case, customers.

Regrettably, I’ll have to return this model and hope that Brooks addresses the issue in next year’s release. Brooks, please: Make Brooks boring again!
review.name: If It Ain’t Broke, Don’t Fix It!

review.reviewBody: Best Adrenaline shoe so far!  Big upgrade from recent versions.  I’ve been running with this style shoe for 10years.  I feel like as the shoe has featured more cushion it’s lost the longevity and stability.  I recently even considered switching models or brands.  This shoe feels elite the second you put them on.  I like them even more the minute I started running.  Great job R&D department!
review.name: Best Adrenaline model yet!

review.reviewBody: Bought these as a gift. They were absolutely perfect and are now well loved!
First time I have bought Brooks and this followed Achilles injury. Have to say that the ankle support is excellent and overall comfort is spot on.
review.name: First time purchase

review.reviewBody:
Excellent shoes. Completed a 13.1 in them. They were very comfortable and a joy to run in.

Brooks feel free to send this shoe to me in size 11 any color I would be more than happy to get professional running pictures done in them.
review.name: Brock’s Brooks

review.reviewBody: I have been a big fan of brooks for sometime. Have worn the Ghost as well as the Adrenaline. The new GTS Adrenaline 24 is simply the best shoe I have ever worn. The DNA Loft v3 is a soft cushion and very light......very comfortable with great support.
Possibly the best brooks I have ran in. 10 plus years using brooks.
I had much better quality and most importantly comfort in the pass.
review.name: Not Impressed

hasVariant.description: Buy the Stan's NoTubes Race Sealant online or shop all Bike from Backcountry.com.

review.reviewBody:
I've been using this sealant for several months and haven't had one flat.  I can't give higher praise then that.  I ride 200 -300 miles/week on average.  I've had cases where I've lost pressure but never enough to make the tire unrideable or even unstable.  Also, unlike other sealants I've used, I've never had the sealant spray drops of sealant out of the tire, which then makes a mess on whatever part of the bike where the sealant lands.

I use the sealant with Continental Grand Prix 5000 AS TR Road Tires.  I mention the tires because they have more rubber on their tread than do the non-AS tires.  So, it may be a combination of both the tires and the sealant that has prevented flats.  Whatever it is, i.e., the sealant alone or the combination of the tires and sealant, I'm not sure but as mentioned, it works.

This sealant is more difficult to use than other sealants but that's a small price to pay considering how well it works.  You can't inject the sealant though the valve stem, even if the core is removed.  Instead, you have to separate the tire from the rim, making enough space to pour the sealant into to tire.  It's not necessary to remove the tire.  You just need to be able to pour the sealant into the the tire.  After the sealant is in the tire, reseat the tire and your ready to go.
review.name: BEST SEALANT I'VE EVER USED

review.reviewBody: The NoBugZone shelter is great on its own, and these sides extend its versatility.  Best part is that the zippers all match up making it easy to get in and out.  This shelter and sides made all the difference on our camping trip, when it rained for 3 days.
review.name: NoBugZone screen shelter & sides

review.reviewBody: These walls are one of the reasons why I bought the NoBugZone 3-in-1 in the first place. I love the fact that there are 4 walls, 3 are solid and there is one wall that has a front middle zipper that you use as an entrance. When unzipped, you can tie them to each side to create an “A” entrance. All walls connect to the corners on the inside of the screenhouse with a plastic clip and the tension can be adjusted easily (loosen or tighten as you wish). There are plastic toggles in between to help keep them in place as well. We just got these, along with our screenhouse, so I haven’t tested them in winds or rain yet, but they seem like they’ll hold up well. Exactly what I expected, I’m very happy with this purchase so far and look forward to testing them out on our family camping trips.

review.reviewBody: I am very happy with these base layers, the color choices are nice too! I do find them to be softer and less itchy than some other wool base layers.  The sizing is pretty standard.  I usually wear small and the small fits me great (waist 27 hip 37). review.itemreviewed: Cedars Merino Lightweight V-Waist Baselayer Bottom - Women's
review.reviewBody: Love how these feel and how soft they are. Excited that they came in green and the color is really nice. Ordered a medium, but need to exchange for a small. I’m 5’6 and 130 lbs, waist 30 inches, and lower hips being 36 inches and they were just a little to loose. Same with the base layer top I ordered to match. I could have kept them and maybe put them in the dryer to shrink, but I’d rather have a small at this price and have them fit the way they should. I’m pretty active and these do show every curve. So if you have any bulges or a tummy then just know these don’t hide anything.
review.name: Love these pants!

review.reviewBody: Tires were on sale for a good price so I figured I would try them out. I had a shop set them up for tubeless. Tires were going flat in between rides. I brought them back to the shop and they found that sealant was seeping through the sidewall on both tires. They did what the could to prevent me from having to buy new tires. I would have to add air before every ride as sealant continued to seep through sidewall just at a slower rate. After many flat tires well out riding I had enough and purchased new tires. I am now out the cost of the tires and the install fees.
review.name: Do not waste your money!

review.reviewBody: I owned this tire for 3 months and 200 miles before the bead tore in a 4 inch section. It was on flat ground on a smooth part of the trail and had not been damaged prior (only 200 miles or less of ride time).   Attempted to warranty directly with Michelin and was asked to take to a bike shop for an inspection. The first person who opened the case for me was fantastic, however my LBS has been trying to settle this for a week now and has not been able to reach someone that can finish the claim (02826286). They’ve been dropped from calls more than once and have now resorted to email. They also told me that if this had been any of the other major tire manufacturers they sell, I would have had a replacement tire in the mail, no questions.   A real shame, as the tire was my favorite over the competitors prior to the warranty experience. Traction and rolling resistance was fantastic while it lasted.
review.name: Torn Bead/warranty a challenge

review.reviewBody: Very disappointed in this tire, I have flatted 4 times in my first 5 rides, and the tire is already starting to crack on the sidewall.
review.name: 4 flats in first 5 rides

review.reviewBody: Very disappointed in this tire, I have flatted 4 times in my first 5 rides, and the tire is already starting to crack on the sidewall.
review.name: 4 flats in first 5 rides

review.reviewBody: I have been riding these tires for just over two years now. Definitely more confidence inspiring than maxxis dhf and dhr ii. It grips better and is more durable than maxxis. It rolls slightly worse but you can carry extra speed in the corners. Casing is also more durable than the exo +. I kept puncturing the exo + casing but have not once punctured the michelin tires where it is not repairable, front or rear. I ride these tires in dry loose trails of socal.
review.name: Can't beat these

review.reviewBody: Bought this tire to replace the Maxxis Rekons on my Scott Spark 950. I have another bike with Schwalbe Magic Mary at front and Hans Dampf at rear and they were great on snow and ice. With more aggressive tire profile, I thought the Wild Enduro would have better grip. I was mistaken big time! This tire doesn’t have any grip on cold, snowy and icy surface. I had to deflate the tire to around 15psi ( i’m 5’11”, 185lbs) in order for it to have at least some grip, and even with that pressure, I had to be really slow otherwise i would have slid all over the place. I had to walk my bike on descents as I would have definitely crashed going down. This tire might be good for tropical weather, but definitely not for the cold north.
review.name: Not for cold weather

review.name: Not for cold weather

review.reviewBody: Covers moon dust to deep mud with competence and no problem areas where it doesn't work. While an Assegai w/Maxxgrip may beat it in the moon dust by a small amount, it weighs about 400g more. A dedicated mud-spike will also be better in the mud. But nothing beats the Wild Enduro as a tire that performs at the highest levels EVERYWHERE. IMO, this is the best tire ever made for the front end of a mt bike.   Rolling resistance is great for what it is, but not great if you compare it to an xc race tire, so it get 3 stars there, but it does roll faster than many other DH type tires so it gets one star back. Hard to judge this one...
review.name: Most Versatile Front Tire Ever

review.reviewBody: Have been running the Wild Enduro Front Magi-X and Wild Enduro Rear GUM-X3D for almost 4 months now and they have been some of the best cornering and root gripping tires that I have owned. Hands down better than the Maxxis Minion DHF and DHR combo that I had on previously. Would buy these again.
review.name: Excellent grip and low rolling resistance

review.reviewBody: Really good on most terrains unless its super GLOOPY muddy. Light enough to make it up all the climbs, strong enough for most descents. I have run these on the rear, but for rougher faster uplifted style terrain such as bike parks they are not quite strong enough and have torn them. I run these front and rear all year in the UK and just change them for alps holidays
review.name: Perfect for most uk riding

review.reviewBody: This unit is not cheap, but I decided to treat myself for my first time trying out chain waxing and I'm so glad I did. It makes the process so easy and I know I'll get many years of use out of it. Silca is a brand that stands behind their product and I find they're always worth the extra buck if you're able to spend it. Some have complained about the small size of the pot, but I find it perfect for one chain. If you're hoping to wax more than one chain at a time, you'll probably need to look elsewhere.
